by Gonswanza » Fri May 13, 2022 1:38 pm

Stupidly common cliche...

War RPs playing out with WWII tactics, from infantry battles to aircraft to naval combat. Especially naval combat.

You don't need LOS to engage a threat, guns are outdated and too short-ranged, and missiles are the go-to weapon in conflicts in the MT era onwards.

Guns are a last resort in aircraft.

In tanks, you see a target, you shoot it, if a UAV above tells you there's armor in an area you have the tools to move and engage quickly to get the jump on them. Angling armor (as in, rotating your turret or hull or the whole tank) is a suicidal tactic, APFSDS can strike against armor well beyond a kilometer away and still have enough energy downrange to kill a tank.

by Bistritza » Fri May 13, 2022 10:49 pm

SOOC:

This was originally a trope online, but over time it became so over-used that it's a cliche; it's opposite still remains a trope. It's a situation.
''now it's OOC, now it's srs bro'', implicitly or explicitly. Basically, ''It's OOC so I'm serious I'm a serious guy IRL bro you went too far''. This cringe has subcategories within it which are also cliches, such as but not all;

  • I play an 'evil' or antagonistic country and I have heel-turned very suddenly and over a small thing. (along with being bs, it's a sin against fourth wall breaks).
  • HELLO ARE WE DISCUSSING SOMETHING CONTROVERSIAL? OH WELL I WRITE IN ALL CAPS NOW TO POTENTIATE HOW SRS IT IS.
  • I'm usually hyperactive but I lost an argument, was betrayed or whatever - Now I will be silent so people notice how upset I am and that it's SRS.
  • Hey I know I usually argue that morality bad but bro you went too far..too soon bro.
So, I guess the thought it: I need social credit virtue signal approval points and I am so moral that I will throw this random person under the bus to get it. Brave.
-The mentioned ''opposite'' is where they take IC too seriously is still somehow a trope, it's not redundant or bland. To be honest, the responses of ''IC is srs'' people are amazing to read sometimes.

Subject title? The whole fallacy of the ''IC/OOC'' strict dichotomy - I'll be addressing that globally soon. It doesn't exist.
